ior Shadow Cabinet appointments|website=[[Labour Party (UK)|The Labour Party]]|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n* Keir Starmer, Leader of the Opposition\n* Angela Rayner, Deputy Leader and Chair of the Labour Party\n* Anneliese Dodds, Shadow Chancellor of the Exchequer\n* Lisa Nandy, Shadow Foreign Secretary\n* Nick Thomas-Symonds, Shadow Home Secretary\n* Rachel Reeves, Shadow Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster\n* Jonathan Ashworth, Shadow Health Secretary\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Official Opposition frontbench]]\n*[[Official Opposition Shadow Cabinet (United Kingdom)]]\n*[[Her Majesty's Most Loyal Opposition (United Kingdom)]]\n*[[List of British shadow cabinets]]\n*[[List of shadow holders of the Great Offices of State]]\n*[[Cabinet of the United Kingdom]]\n*[[British Government frontbench]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{British shadow cabinets}}\n{{UK Shadow Cabinet}}\n{{UK Labour Party}}\n\n[[Category:British shadow cabinets]]\n[[Category:Official Opposition (United Kingdom)]]\n[[Category:2020 in British politics]]\n", "text_old": "{{Recentism|date=April 2020}}<!--per [[WP:MOS]], don't use Sir in prose-->\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n[[Keir Starmer]] became [[Leader of the Opposition (United Kingdom)|Leader of the Opposition]] after being elected as [[Leader of the Labour Party (UK)|Leader of the Labour Party]] on 4 April 2020.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-52164589|title=Keir Starmer elected as new Labour leader|work=[[BBC News]]|date=4 April 2020|access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref> Starmer appointed his Shadow Cabinet on 5 and 6 April.\n\n== Background ==\n{{main|2020 Labour Party leadership election}}\nFollowing the defeat of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] in the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]], former leader [[Jeremy Corbyn]] stepped down and triggered a leadership election that would elect a new party leader and a new [[Leader of the Opposition (UK)|Leader of the Opposition]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election-2019-50787431|title=General election 2019: Does Labour need a new direction after Corbyn?|website=[[BBC News]]|first=Iain|last=Watson|date=13 December 2019|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> Six candidates declared for the election, with three receiving sufficient nominations to advance to the ballot. [[Keir Starmer]], MP for [[Holborn and St Pancras]] and [[Shadow Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union]], was elected over [[Rebecca Long-Bailey]] and [[Lisa Nandy]].\n\n== Shadow Cabinet ==\n{{Keir Starmer shadow cabinet vertical}}\n==Shadow Ministers by department==\nShadow Ministers were originally appointed on 9 April 2020:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://labour.org.uk/press/keir-starmer-appoints-labour-frontbench/|title=Keir Starmer appoints Labour frontbench|website=The Labour Party|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref> Positions in '''bold''' denote a position in the Shadow Cabinet.\n\n=== Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" style=\"width: 1px; background: {{House of Commons/meta/color}};\" |\n| style=\"width: 450px;\" |[[Shadow Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy|'''Shadow Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy''']]\n| style=\"width: 320px;\" |'''{{small|The Rt Hon}} [[Ed Miliband]] {{small|MP}}'''\n|-\n|Shadow Minister of State for Science, Research and Digital\n|[[Chi Onwurah]] {{small|MP}} {{small|(jointly with DCMS)}}\n|-\n|Shadow Minister of State for Climate Change\n|[[Matthew Pennycook]] {{small|MP}}\n|-\n|Shadow Minister of State for Business and Consumers\n|[[Lucy Powell]] {{small|MP}}\n|-\n|Shadow Minister of State for Green New Deal and Energy \n|[[Alan Whitehead]] {{small|MP}}\n|}\n\n=== Cabinet Office ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" style=\"width: 1px; background: {{House of Commons/meta/color}};\" |\n| style=\"width: 450px;\" |'''[[Shadow Ch